temberg":"Sindelfingen, Böblingen, Württemberg, Germany","Württemberg, Heiliges Römisches Reich":"Württemberg","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Reiser","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Erwin, Kurt, Otto, Hannelore, Heiner, Helmut, Markus, Siegfried, Willi.","German: habitational name for someone from Reis in Bavaria or Reissen in Thuringia (see   Reis   1).","German and Swiss German: occupational name from Middle High German <i>reisære</i> ‘warrior, traveler (on horseback)’."],"variants":[{"name":"Raiser","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Manfred.","German: variant of   Reiser  ."]},{"name":"Reisig","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Erna, Gerhard, Heinz.","German: nickname from Middle High German <i>reisec</i>, Middle Low German <i>reisich</i> ‘armed for war’, later ‘sprightly, tall’. See also   Reiser   2."]},{"name":"Rizer","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Reiser  ."]},{"name":"Ryser","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans, Armin, Klaus, Otto, Urs.","Swiss German: variant of   Reiser   1."]},{"name":"Rieser","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Aloys, Ernst, Fritz, Hannelore, Hans, Manfred, Ruedi, Volker.  French Norvin, Alain, Marcel.","German:","Alemannic form of   Reiser  ."]},{"name":"Reisner","meanings":["German: probably a habitational name for someone from a place called Reisen in Bavaria, Reissen in Thuringia, or Reussen on the Saale river.","German: variant of   Reiser   2.","German: from an agent derivative of Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>rīse</i> ‘veil’; perhaps an occupational name for someone who made veils."]},{"name":"Reis","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Manuel, Jose, Carlos, Luis, Jorge, Alberto, Julio, Luiz, Alvaro, Francisco, Geraldo, Juanita.  Portuguese Joao, Paulo, Guilherme, Serafim, Afonso, Duarte, Henrique, Joaquim, Marcio.","German: from Middle High German <i>rīs</i> ‘undergrowth, brushwood’; a topographic name for someone who lived in an overgrown area, or a habitational name from Reis or Reissen in Bavaria.","German: occupational name for a cobbler, Middle High German <i>riuze</i>. Compare   Reuss  ."]},{"name":"Reisinger","meanings":["German:","habitational name for someone from any of several places called Reising or Reisingen in Bavaria.","occupational name for a soldier, from Middle High German <i>reisinc</i> ‘warrior’, literally ‘traveler’ (see   Reiser  )."]},{"name":"Riser","meanings":["Swiss German: topographic name for someone who lived near a thicket or underbrush, from an agent noun based on Middle High German <i>rīs</i> ‘branch, shrubbery’.","Possibly an Americanized form of German   Reiser  ."]}]},{"name":"Agata","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Agatha</b>   in main dictionary."],"variants":[{"name":"Agda","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Agatha</b>   in main dictionary."]},{"name":"Ågot","meanings":["variant of   Agata ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Agata Reiser was born in 1540, in Württemberg. She married Andreas Heimsamer in 1557, in Sindelfingen, Böblingen, Württemberg, Germany. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in March 1584, in Sindelfingen, Böblingen, Württemberg, Germany, at the age of 44."},"et":{"1540–März 1584":"1540–märts 1584","1531–1568":"1531–1568","1561–Male":"1561–Surnud","1563–Male":"1563–Surnud","1565–1634":"1565–1634","1540–1584":"1540–1584","Juli 1563":"juuli 1563","November 1561":"november 1561","1561":"1561","September 1565":"september 1565","26. April 1568":"26. aprill 1568","1557":"1557","März 1584":"märts 1584","1634":"1634","1568":"1568","1565":"1565","1531":"1531","1563":"1563","1540":"1540","1584":"1584","Sindelfingen, Böblingen, Württemberg":"Sindelfingen, Kreis Böblingen, Württemberg, Saksamaa","Württe